#compdef lmstfy
# ============================================================================
# lmstfy - Let Me Schedule This For You: a task queue with REST API (Go, MIT)
#
# Author : bitleak team
# Upstream: https://github.com/bitleak/lmstfy
#
# lmstfy (pronounced "let-me-schedule-this-for-you") is a Redis-
# backed REST task queue. Producers POST JSON job records (`body`,
# `tries`, `delay`, `tt l`) to the lmstfy HTTP API; lmstfy assigns
# each job a ULID, stores it in Redis under the configured queue +
# namespace, and tracks per-job state (delayed -> ready -> reserved
# -> acked / nacked / dead). Consumers GET reserve jobs in a long-
# poll style, acknowledge (DELETE) on success or nack (PUT) for
# retry with exponential backoff. Multi-token auth + per-token
# throttler + dead-letter queue + cluster-aware engine
# coordination via the Redis admin database.
#
# CLI flags:
#   -c <file>     - config TOML file (default conf/config.toml)
#   -v            - print version
#   -bt <level>   - log backtrack level (default warn)
#   -sv           - dev mode: skip token verification
#   -p <pid>      - PID file (default running.pid)
#
# The ULID lane is built on `github.com/oklog/ulid v2` (declared
# at upstream go.mod HEAD), the canonical Go ULID library by Peter
# Bourgon's oklog org (github.com/oklog/ulid, 5000+ stars). The
# library implements the ULID spec (Feerasta, 2016) byte-for-byte:
# 48-bit Unix-ms timestamp + 80-bit randomness, encoded as 26
# Crockford-Base32 characters. Provides a monotonic generator for
# burst writes (`ulid.Monotonic(rand.Reader, 0)`) to avoid sort-
# order collisions when multiple ULIDs are minted in the same
# millisecond. lmstfy uses ULID as the per-job unique identifier
# because the lexicographic time-ordering matches Redis sorted-
# set scoring naturally - new jobs sort to the end without an
# extra timestamp column.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 219 :: ULID (Universally Unique Lexicographically Sortable Identifier)
# Round 1356 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 219
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : dylanhart/ulid-rs                  [R1355 _idt]
#   Go      : oklog/ulid                         [R1356 THIS FILE]
#   TS/Node : ulid/javascript                    [R1357 closing]
#
# oklog/ulid is structurally interesting in this axis: it sits at
# 5000+ stars - more than `dylanhart/ulid-rs` (470) and
# `ulid/javascript` (3800) combined despite each lane having
# similar developer-population sizes. The Go-ecosystem skew toward
# operational tooling (Kafka clients, task queues, log shippers,
# observability backends) selects strongly for ULID adoption -
# every Go observability tool that needs to ID its records picks
# oklog/ulid as the de-facto choice.
# ============================================================================

_lmstfy() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '-c[config TOML file (default conf/config.toml)]:file:_files -g "*.toml"' \
        '-v[show version]' \
        '-bt[log backtrack level (panic|fatal|error|warn|info|debug|trace)]:level:(panic fatal error warn info debug trace)' \
        '-sv[dev mode: skip token verification]' \
        '-p[PID file path (default running.pid)]:file:_files' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]'
}

_lmstfy "$@"
